{
  "texts": [
    "Although it often yields strong results, it is computationally intensive.",
    "The objective of SFT is to minimize the loss calculated on the output portion of the training sequence:L SFT (Θ) = E x∼DSFT   - i∈{output} log p(x i | x 0, x 1,..., x i-1; Θ)  ,(2)where Θ denotes the model parameters, D SFT represents the fine-tuning dataset, and x = (x 0, x 1,...) refers to the tokenized input sequence.",
    "Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT)Since SFT updates all model parameters, the computational cost can be prohibitive, particularly for large-scale LLMs.",
    "Furthermore, domain-specific data is often limited compared to the vast general-purpose datasets used in pretraining, making full fine-tuning impractical in many cases.",
    "Parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) offers a more resource-efficient alternative by modifying only a subset of parameters while preserving most of the pretrained model's knowledge."
  ]
}